# Case study headings

Use the editorial components in `case-study-prose.tsx` — do not invent new heading styles.

## Component map

| Component | Use for |
|-----------|---------|
| `CaseStudyYear` | Year above hero title, or editorial band labels |
| `CaseStudyH2` | Main section headings in long-form case studies |
| `CaseStudyH3` | Subsections inside a prose band |
| `CaseStudySubheading` | Section headings in shorter / bento case studies |

## Casing rules

### `CaseStudyYear` labels → ALL CAPS only

Use for fixed editorial labels, not body copy:

```tsx
<CaseStudyYear>PROJECT OVERVIEW</CaseStudyYear>
```

Numeric years stay as-is: `<CaseStudyYear>{content.year}</CaseStudyYear>`.

### `CaseStudyH2`, `CaseStudyH3`, `CaseStudySubheading` → title case

- Capitalise major words (nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs).
- Lowercase short articles, conjunctions, and prepositions (`a`, `an`, `the`, `and`, `but`, `or`, `for`, `at`, `in`, `on`, `to`, `with`) unless they are the first word.
- Keep proper nouns and brand names as-is: **Saltbot**, **FreshPrints**, **Piggy**.
- **Never** use ALL CAPS for these components.

### `CaseStudyMedia` / `CaseStudyBento` image `caption` → title case

Captions render as `<figcaption>` via `CaseStudyMedia` (`caption` on bento cells, or `label` when used as caption text).

Apply the **same title case rules** as headings:

- Capitalise major words; lowercase short articles, conjunctions, and prepositions unless first word.
- **Never** use ALL CAPS for captions.
- Multi-line captions (`<>...</>`): title-case the lead line; supporting lines may stay sentence case when they read as body copy.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
caption: "Rewarding Users on Their Decisions"
caption: "Recognition for Their Consistency"
caption: (
  <>
    Customize Your Alerts
    <br />
    Get notified whenever a metric is broken
  </>
)

// ❌ BAD
caption: "REWARDING USERS ON THEIR DECISIONS"
caption: "Celebrating their wins"
caption: "recognition for their consistency"
```

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
<CaseStudyH2>Clarity at First Glance</CaseStudyH2>
<CaseStudyH2>The Problem with Prompting</CaseStudyH2>
<CaseStudyH2>Why Saltbot?</CaseStudyH2>

// ❌ BAD
<CaseStudyH2>CLARITY AT FIRST GLANCE</CaseStudyH2>
<CaseStudyH2>The problem</CaseStudyH2>
<CaseStudyH2>the solution</CaseStudyH2>
```

## British English

Match body copy: `Customise`, `Personalised`, `behaviour` where appropriate. Brand names follow project spelling rules in `spelling.mdc`.

## Before finishing case study edits

Scan every `CaseStudyH2`, `CaseStudyH3`, `CaseStudySubheading`, and image `caption` string for sentence case or ALL CAPS and normalise to title case.
